\name{plot.gradientForest}
\Rdversion{1.1}
\alias{plot.gradientForest}

%- Also NEED an '\alias' for EACH other topic documented here.
\title{
Plots for gradientForest objects
}
\description{
Plot method for the gradientForest objects. 

}
\usage{
\method{plot}{gradientForest}(x,	plot.type=c("Overall.Importance","Split.Density",
"Cumulative.Importance","Performance")[1], par.args=NULL, plot.args=NULL,...)
}
%- maybe also 'usage' for other objects documented here.
\arguments{
  \item{x}{
    an object of class \code{gradientForest} generated by \code{\link{gradientForest}}.
  }


   \item{plot.type}{
    specifies the type of plot defined for the object.  Current choices for
    gradientForest objects are \code{"Overall.Importance"}, \code{"Split.Density"}, 
    \code{"Cumulative.Importance"} and \code{"Performance"}. Default \code{"Overall.Importance"}.
  }
      \item{par.args}{a list object with arguments to be passed on to be used by \code{\link{par}} according 
      the \code{plot.type} chosen.  See Details for the defaults for each plot type.}
      
      \item{plot.args}{a list object with arguments to be passed on according 
      the \code{plot.type} chosen.  See Details for the defaults for each plot type.}

  
  \item{\ldots}{further arguments passed to or from other methods. When \code{plot.type} is set to \code{"Split.Density"} or
\code{"Cumulative.Importance"}, the following two arguments are available:
         \describe{
    \item{\code{imp.vars}:}{
    a character vector of names of predictor variables (currently limited to
    two variables). This vector required for the second and third plot types
    described below.  Default (\code{imp.vars=NULL}) is to use the predictor variables
    that explain the two highest \eqn{R^2} in the overall importance plot type.
  }

  \item{\code{imp.vars.names}:}{
    more descriptive names for the predictor variables to be used as labels
    on the plots.  Default is set to predictor variable names given in \code{imp.vars}.
  } }

}
        
}
\details{
%%  ~~ If necessary, more details than the description above ~~
The following are the default settings when \code{par.args=NULL} for each plot type. See  \code{\link{par}} for the definition of each of the arguments.



 Overall.Importance: \code{list(mfrow = c(1, 2), mar = c(4, 6, 2, 1))} 
  
 Split.Density: \code{list(mar =c(4.5, 1.5, 0.5, 4.5), omi = c(0.1, 0.25, 0.1, 0.1))}. 
       
 Cumulative.Importance: \code{list(mar=c(0.0,2.1,1.1,0), omi=c(0.75, 0.75, 0.1, 0.1))}. 
 See plot.args below for the definitions for \code{show.species} and \code{show.overall}. 
 
 Performance: \code{list(mfrow=c(1,1))}
 

The following are the default settings when \code{plot.args=NULL} for each plot type.

Overall.Importance: \code{list(cex.axis = 0.7, cex.names = cex.axis, las=1,horiz = TRUE)}
  
Split.Density: \code{list(leg.posn="topright",bin=FALSE, }\code{nbin=101, leg.panel=1, barwidth=1, }\code{cex.legend=0.8, line.ylab=1.5)}
  
Cumulative.Importance: \code{list(leg.posn="topleft",Legend=TRUE,}\code{common.scale=FALSE, line.ylab=1.0,}\code{ cex.legend=0.75,
 show.species=TRUE,show.overall=TRUE,leg.nspecies=10)}, where \code{leg.nspecies} is set to the
number of species in the legend (in order of importance) for cumulative importance plot. If \code{common.scale} 
is \code{TRUE} the scale of the y axis is the same for all panels. If
\code{show.species} is \code{TRUE} the species cumulative curves are shown, and if \code{show.overall} 
the overall cumulative curves are shown.
             
            
Performance: \code{list(horizontal = FALSE, }\code{show.names = FALSE, }\code{las=2,}\code{cex.axis = 0.7,}\code{cex.labels=0.7,}\code{line=2)}, where \code{show.names} is
set to \code{TRUE} or \code{FALSE} to override the defaults on whether an x-axis label on the performance plot is printed for each group.

}


\value{

The overall importance plot shows a simple barplot of the ranked importances of
the physical variables. The most reliable importances are the \eqn{R^2} weighted importances.

The split density plot shows the density of splits, the density of the data and the ratio
of the densities for the the chosen physical variables.

The cumulative importance plot is an integrated form of the split density plot.
The cumulative importance is plotted separately for all species and averaged over all species.
The cumulative importance can be interpreted as a mapping from an environmental gradient on to biological gradient

The performance plot shows the goodness of fit performance measures for all
species for which the physical variables have some predictive power. For
regression, the measure is out-of-bag \eqn{R^2}. For classification, the measure is
out-of-bag error rate.

}
